'''Noyyal''' is a {{cvt|180|km}}–long seasonal river in [[Kongu Nadu|Western Tamil Nadu]], India. It is a tributary of the [[Kaveri]] river. The river rises in the Vellingiri hills in the [[Western Ghats]], and flows westwards through the cities of [[Coimbatore]], and [[Tirupur]], before draining into the Kaveri at Noyyal in [[Karur district]]. The river basin covers an area of {{cvt|3500|km2}}, which consists of {{cvt|1800|km2}} of cultivable lands.


The river is seasonal, and dependent on the [[monsoon]]. An extensive tank system has been developed to store the river water and the overflow during monsoon. Kausika river, which originates along the northern side of the [[Coimbatore district]] in the Western Ghats, is the major tributary of the river.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/Crisis/river-noyyal.htm|title=River Noyyal|work=Rain water harvesting |access-date=1 June 2015}}</ref> Flowing through major urban areas, the river is highly polluted and faces significant ecological concern.

'''Therabene''' is an American [[biotechnology]] company founded in 2020. It researches a class of drugs called [[Proteolysis targeting chimera|PROTAC]]<nowiki/>s, which are designed to degrade disease-related proteins, with a focus on targets such as [[Cyclin-dependent kinase 9|CDK9]] and [[MYC]] for [[Cancer treatment|cancer therapy]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Koirala |first1=Mahesh |last2=DiPaola |first2=Mario |title=Targeting CDK9 in Cancer: An Integrated Approach of Combining In Silico Screening with Experimental Validation for Novel Degraders |journal=PubMed Central |url=https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10968976 |access-date=January 16, 2026}}</ref>
== History ==
Therabene was founded in 2020 by Mario DiPaola, initially operating from the Mansfield Bio-Incubator.<ref>{{cite web |title=Company Spotlight: Therabene |url=https://www.bioinc.org/news/2022/1/12/company-spotlight-therabene |website=Mansfield Bio-Incubator |access-date=January 16, 2026 |date=January 12, 2022}}</ref> The company later relocated its headquarters to [[Norwood, Massachusetts]].<ref name="PharmiWeb">{{cite web |title=Therabene Inc. Appoints Dr. Oscar L. Kashala as Chief Medical Officer and Executive Vice President of Global Clinical Development |url=https://www.pharmiweb.com/press-release/2025-08-06/therabene-inc-appoints-dr-oscar-l-kashala-as-chief-medical-officer-and-executive-vice-president-o |website=PharmiWeb.com |access-date=January 16, 2026 |date=August 6, 2025}}</ref> In October 2022, Therabene raised $50,000 in debt financing and subsequently $1+M in equity financing.<ref name="cbinsights">{{cite web |title=Therabene - Products, Competitors, Financials, Employees, Headquarters Locations |url=https://www.cbinsights.com/company/therabene |website=CB Insights |access-date=January 16, 2026 |date=August 6, 2025}}</ref>

In November 2024, the company announced preclinical results for two molecules showing tumor reduction in a [[triple-negative breast cancer]] model.<ref>{{cite web |title=Therabene molecules show promise in triple-negative breast cancer model |url=https://www.bioworld.com/articles/714740-therabene-molecules-show-promise-in-triple-negative-breast-cancer-model |website=BioWorld |access-date=January 16, 2026 |date=November 22, 2024}}</ref> In August 2025, Therabene appointed Oscar L. Kashala as chief medical officer to advance its clinical pipeline.<ref>{{cite web |title=Therabene Inc. Appoints Oscar L. Kashala as CMO and EVP of Global Clinical Development |url=https://firstwordpharma.com/story/5986968 |website=FirstWord Pharma |access-date=January 16, 2026 |date=August 6, 2025}}</ref><ref name="MedPath">{{cite web |title=Therabene Appoints Dr. Oscar Kashala as CMO to Advance Protein Degrader Pipeline for Hard-to-Treat Cancers |url=https://trial.medpath.com/news/494d6ec59a4f762d/therabene-appoints-dr-oscar-kashala-as-cmo-to-advance-protein-degrader-pipeline-for-hard-to-treat-cancers |website=MedPath |access-date=January 16, 2026}}</ref>

==Pollution==
⚫
At [[Truro Crown Court]] in December 2021, Dairy Crest admitted charges relating to a series of incidents of serious pollution between December 2015 and January 2021, including the illegal discharge of "biological sludge" and "suspended solids" from its creamery at [[Davidstow]] into the [[River Inny (Cornwall)|River Inny]], Cornwall.<ref>{{cite news|title=Discharge from Davidstow Cathedral City cheese factory poisoned fish|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cornwall-59597830 |work=BBC News|date=10 December 2021|accessdate=13 December 2021}}</ref> Fines of £1.52 million and costs of £272,747 were imposed on the company in June 2022.<ref>{{cite news|title=Davidstow Cathedral City cheese firm pollution fine|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cornwall-61914566|work=BBC News|date=23 June 2022|accessdate=23 June 2022}}</ref>

In 2025 the company said it was making the switch from producing demineralised whey and galacto-oligosaccharides, which it began producing in 2013 in order to return to the production of sweet whey powder.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Cornwall's Davidstow Creamery to lose 60 jobs amid Saputo Dairy cuts |url=https://www.thepost.uk.com/news/cornwalls-davidstow-creamery-to-lose-60-jobs-amid-saputo-dairy-cuts-780443}}</ref>

The company has also polluted other rivers in the UK. Pollution in 2023 and 2025 in a tributary of the River Ure was caused by a faulty drainage system at it's Wensleydale Creamery in Hawes.<ref>{{Cite news |title=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/ckg1pz2kxkpo}}</ref>

Saputo's other international subsidiaries have also been prosecuted for pollution. An accident at a facility in Tulare, California on June 22, 2018, led to the release of 5,690 pounds of anhydrous ammonia. Owned by Saputo Cheese USA Inc. the facility produced mozzarella cheese and whey protein concentrate. <ref>{{Cite web |title=Central Valley’s Saputo Cheese Agrees to $170,000 Penalty for Clean Air Act Violations |url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/central-valleys-saputo-cheese-agrees-170000-penalty-clean-air-act-violations}}</ref>
